#### Closures enable a strong contract

The variable is conceptually ‚Äúsaved‚Äù inside the object returned from the function thanks to Javascript closures. This means that we can set the value with the setter method (i.e. x.set(2)), but attempting to directly change the field (i.e. x.myVal = 2) won‚Äôt do anything.

The greatest part of having these explicit setters and getters is that the object now has a strong contract/interface with the outside world. The state is fully encapsulated and the only ways in and out of the object is through the setters and getters.

One drawback about using closures is the issue of performance. While there doesn‚Äôt seem to be any difference when creating an object, method calls on the object using closures were about 80% slower.

### How do we achieve data encapsulation with Javascript objects?

Private member variables in objects.

**All properties or let us say member variables defined with the "this" keyword inside a function object is of public type, which mean that they can be accessed from outside of a created object.**

