The ‚Äúrequest‚Äù function below, takes a function as its last argument. This function is not executed together with the code above. It is saved to be executed later once the underlying I/O operation of fetching data over HTTP(s) is done. The underlying HTTP(s) request is an asynchronous operation and does not block the execution of the rest of the JavaScript code. The callback function is put on a sort of queue called the ‚Äúevent loop‚Äù until it will be executed with a result from the request.

Callbacks are a good way to declare what will happen once an I/O operation has a result, but what if you want to use that data in order to make another request? You can only handle the result of the request (if we use the example above) within the callback function provided.

